The block's gas limit in #Ethereum serves the same purpose as the block's size limit in #Bitcoin.

They both preserve #Decentralization through limiting the computational work needs to be done by nodes.

6/

Gas is the fundamental unit of computation in #Ethereum; which means that one computational step requires one unit of gas.

For example, a simple #ETH transfer would require 21,000 units of gas to be executed (21,000 computational steps).

4/

To preserve decentralization in #Ethereum, i.e. limit the computational work that needs to be done by nodes; users must specify the amount of computation needed to execute their transactions.

This is done through: Gas.

3/

In #Ethereum, a transaction can be small in size, but trigger a large amount of computation through a contract (e.g. contract that calculates one million hashes).

Therefore, a size limit cannot be used to preserve decentralization.
